The patient presents with acute scrotal pain, dysuria, urgency, and elevated white blood cells in urine — classic features of a lower urinary tract infection. While gram-negative bacteria like *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* could cause urethritis, the absence of purulent discharge makes this less likely. However, chlamydial infections commonly present with asymptomatic or mild urethritis and can progress to epididymitis or orchitis due to ascending bacterial spread. Notably, testicular ultrasound reveals increased vascularity consistent with inflammatory processes rather than tumors or varicoceles. Given that *Chlamydia trachomatis* is the most common causative agent of uncomplicated genitourinary infections in young men without overt discharge, and given its strong association with post-urethral inflammation progressing to testicular involvement, C is best supported by the clinical picture and available data.

